@NODE Introducing "Introducing DOSTrace"
@TOC Main

       DOSTrace is a program that allows you to monitor what AmigaDOS
     is doing while you are working with your Amiga. You can watch
     which files your programs use, if they find all the files they
     require, where they are looking for them and much other activity
     of that kind.  

       If this sounds familiar to you, you must be one of the many
     SnoopDos users in the Amiga community.  This tool was written to
     replace SnoopDos.  It shows you a lot more information than
     SnoopDos and it does this in a verbose way.  SnoopDos is written
     by Eddy Carroll and freely distributable.  

       DOSTrace software and documentation are copyright © 1993 by
     Peter Stuer.  All rights reserved.  

@ENDNODE

@NODE Requirements "System Requirements"
@TOC Main

       DOSTrace should run on any Amiga system with at least 512K RAM
     and one disk-drive.  DOSTrace requires KickStart v2.04 or higher
     to run.  Special care has been taken in the program design to
     make the program work with 68020, 68030 and 68040 processors
     without sacrificing 68000 compatibility.  

       Should you have any trouble running DOSTrace on your machine,
     please write to me with the full specifications of your machine,
     that is KickStart version, model, expansion boards etc...  

       DOSTrace is KickStart 3.0 compatible and aware.  It will show
     you some of the new features available with this version of the
     operating system.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Usage "Usage"
@TOC Main

       DOSTrace can be started from the Shell or the Workbench.  

       To start DOSTrace from the Shell simply type: 

             1> DOSTrace 

     followed by a return.  This loads the DOSTrace program and
     starts it.  DOSTrace will then open its window and will start
     monitoring AmigaDOS.  By default DOSTrace will open a window
     that is as wide and as high as the default public screen (most
     of the times, the Workbench screen) without overlapping the
     title bar.  

       If you run DOSTrace with a questionmark (?) as argument you'll
     get the argument template: 

             OUTPUT: 

       If you want the output to appear somewhere else simply add a
     filename or device specification after the command: 

             1> DOSTrace PRT: 

     will send all output to the printer. To save the output to a
     file: 

             1> DOSTrace RAM:SomeFile 

       To start DOSTrace from the Workbench, simply click on the
     accompanying icon and DOSTrace starts.  

       Adding the OUTPUT tooltype to the DOSTrace icon will have the
     same effect as with Shell usage: 

             OUTPUT=CON:/18//300/DOSTrace 

     will open a console window at position (0,18) that is the full
     with of the Workbench screen and 300 lines high.  

       You can also use the Execute Command item from the Workbench
     menu to run DOSTrace.  

       The output can be stopped at any time by pressing Control-C.  

@ENDNODE

@NODE Output "About the output"
@TOC Main

       DOSTrace monitors a lot more AmigaDOS activity than SnoopDOS.
     Currently the following functions are monitored: 

             AddBuffers      LoadSeg 
             CreateDir       Lock 
             CurrentDir      MakeLink 
             DeleteFile      Open 
             DeviceProc      ParentDir 
             ExAll           Rename 
             Examine         SetComment 
             ExamineFH       SetOwner 
             Execute         StartNotify 
             GetDeviceProc   SystemTagList 
             Info 

       The information shown depends on which function is being
     traced but all messages of 3 components in common: 

             Process Name    The name of the process calling the 
                             AmigaDOS function.  

             Trace Info      Verbose information about the function 
                             being executed.  

             Result          Whether the call was succesfull or not 
                             (if applicable) 

@ENDNODE

@NODE About  "About the author and the program"
